'''归因'''（attribution），也译作'''归责'''<ref name="Roberts2017">{{cite book|author=Anthea Roberts|title=Is International Law International?|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=oH8yDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA382|year=2017|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=|pages=382–}}</ref>，是将[[法律责任|法律责任]]延伸至实际未实施[[犯罪|犯罪]]行为的[[被告|被告]]的[[法律|法律]][[学说|学说]]<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=jkxlNQ9uPyUC&pg=PP347 Rethinking Criminal Law] {{Wayback|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jkxlNQ9uPyUC&pg=PP347 |date=20170216202655 }}, 2000, [[Oxford_University_Press|Oxford University Press]], George P.Fletcher,</ref>{{rp|347}} <ref name=CL/>{{rp|665}}。“归因”这一概念是由[[奥地利|奥地利]][[心理学家|心理学家]][[弗里茨·海德|弗里茨·海德]]于1927年提出<ref name="Hunt2015">{{cite book|author=Morton Hunt|title=心理学简史: 当代文丛 - PSYCHOLOGY|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=CYzoCgAAQBAJ&pg=PT364|date=2015-11-13|publisher=[[谷月社|谷月社]]|pages=364–|id=GGKEY:HLGZ20HHKUQ|access-date=2020-07-24|archive-date=2020-07-28|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200728033851/https://books.google.com/books?id=CYzoCgAAQBAJ&pg=PT364|dead-url=no}}</ref>，他认为人类对于已经发生事件的原因的「社会推论」或「知觉感受」。这是对于过去记忆的回溯，也是一种找寻「最初发心」的溯因推理<ref name="方伟达2018">{{cite book|author=方伟达|title=人文社科研究方法--艺术;人文与社会学科，研究生完全达阵祕技|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ntGmDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT196|date=2018-07-09|publisher=五南图书出版股份有限公司|isbn=|pages=196–|access-date=2020-07-24|archive-date=2020-08-12|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200812000818/https://books.google.com/books?id=ntGmDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT196|dead-url=no}}</ref>。也就是说，“归因”起初是一个[[社会心理学|社会心理学]]概念<ref>{{cite book|title=诉讼法学・司法制度|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=LVU5AQAAIAAJ|year=2006|publisher=[[中国人民大学书报资料中心|中国人民大学书报资料中心]]|access-date=2020-07-24|archive-date=2020-08-12|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200812184326/https://books.google.com/books?id=LVU5AQAAIAAJ|dead-url=no}}</ref>。后来，这一概念延伸至法律领域。

法律层面上的归因例子包括：[[转承责任|转承责任]]（vicarious liability，将他人的行为被推定或“归于”被告）、[[犯罪未遂|犯罪未遂]]（即使从未完成）和[[共谋罪|共谋罪]]（conspiracy，未完成或由他人在共谋中实施）<ref name=CL>[https://law.stanford.edu/publications/criminal-law-cases-and-materials-7th-edition/ Criminal Law - Cases and Materials] {{Wayback|url=https://law.stanford.edu/publications/criminal-law-cases-and-materials-7th-edition/ |date=20181004142121 }}, 7th ed. 2012, [[Wolters_Kluwer_Law_&_Business|Wolters Kluwer Law & Business]]; [[John_Kaplan_(law_professor)|John Kaplan]], [[Robert_Weisberg|Robert Weisberg]], [[Guyora_Binder|Guyora Binder]],</ref>{{rp|665}}。

